  :prose
"(chapter
  :n 21
  :title \"Compilers — how a program becomes a program\"
  :book \"book-of-cs-curriculum\"

  :scene
  \"You type code. Something reads the text. Something turns the text
   into a tree. Something walks the tree and makes sure it makes
   sense. Something turns the tree into machine instructions. The
   instructions run. Every one of those steps is a compiler phase.\"

  :the-phases
  (\"lexing (scanning) — text becomes tokens (identifiers, keywords,
    literals, operators)\"
   \"parsing — tokens become a tree (the AST — abstract syntax tree)\"
   \"semantic analysis — types are checked, scopes are resolved,
    references are wired up\"
   \"intermediate representation (IR) — the AST is lowered into a
    simpler, machine-agnostic form\"
   \"optimization — the IR is transformed for speed and space
    (constant folding, dead-code elimination, inlining, loop
    unrolling, register allocation)\"
   \"code generation — the IR becomes target-specific machine or
    bytecode\"
   \"linking — separately compiled pieces are combined into an
    executable\")

  :lexing-briefly
  \"A lexer turns a stream of characters into a stream of tokens. It
   is usually described by regular expressions. 'while' is a
   keyword token. '42' is an integer literal token. 'x' is an
   identifier token. Whitespace between tokens is typically discarded.\"

  :parsing-briefly
  \"A parser turns tokens into a tree. Two main families. Top-down
   (LL, recursive descent) — start from the whole program shape and
   descend. Bottom-up (LR, LALR) — accumulate tokens until a rule
   fires. Parser generators (yacc, bison, ANTLR) automate the
   creation of parsers from grammar files.\"

  :ir
  \"The IR is the compiler's real workspace. Common IR designs: SSA
   (static single assignment — every variable is assigned exactly
   once); three-address code (each statement has at most three
   operands, mimicking simple machines). LLVM IR is the modern
   industry standard for shared cross-language optimization.\"

  :where-in-the-world
  \"Every language you use runs its own compiler or interpreter.
   GCC, LLVM/Clang for C/C++. javac for Java. Python's CPython
   compiles to bytecode then interprets. V8 JIT-compiles JavaScript.
   Rust's rustc uses LLVM. Scheme has many implementations, some
   interpreted, some compiled.\"

  :scheme-code
  \"; A tiny expression evaluator — the last few compiler phases
   ; wrapped into one function

   (define (eval-expr expr env)
     (cond
       ((number? expr) expr)
       ((symbol? expr) (lookup env expr))
       ((pair? expr)
        (case (car expr)
          ((+) (+ (eval-expr (cadr expr) env) (eval-expr (caddr expr) env)))
          ((-) (- (eval-expr (cadr expr) env) (eval-expr (caddr expr) env)))
          ((*) (* (eval-expr (cadr expr) env) (eval-expr (caddr expr) env)))
          ((if) (if (eval-expr (cadr expr) env)
                    (eval-expr (caddr expr) env)
                    (eval-expr (cadddr expr) env)))
          (else (error 'unknown-op (car expr)))))))

   (eval-expr '(if (+ 1 1) 42 99) '())  ; => 42\"

  :philosophy-lens
  \"Aristotle's four causes fit compilers cleanly. Material — the
   source text. Formal — the language's grammar and semantics.
   Efficient — the compiler itself. Final — a runnable program.
   Wittgenstein-late — the semantic phase enforces that variable
   uses respect scoping rules that are the language community's
   meaning of scope.\")

(chapter
  :n 22
  :title \"Databases — the shape of remembering at scale\"
  :book \"book-of-cs-curriculum\"

  :scene
  \"You have a shop with 20,000 items and 5,000 customers and 80,000
   orders. You want to know: which customer has spent the most in
   the last 90 days on items in category X. You cannot walk the
   whole file to answer this in a reasonable time. You need
   structure. That structure is a database.\"

  :the-relational-model
  \"Codd's 1970 paper laid it out. Data lives in tables (relations).
   Each row is a tuple. Each column is an attribute with a type.
   Rows can reference other tables' rows via foreign keys. Queries
   are declarative — say what you want, not how to compute it.

   The relational model rests on set theory and first-order logic.
   The query language, SQL, is a declarative language whose
   semantics are relational algebra. Joins, selections, projections,
   aggregations.\"

  :acid
  \"The properties a transactional database guarantees:
   Atomicity — either the whole transaction happens or none of it.
   Consistency — the database moves from valid state to valid state.
   Isolation — concurrent transactions appear to run sequentially.
   Durability — committed changes survive crashes.\"

  :indexes
  \"Indexes are data structures (usually B-trees, sometimes hash
   tables) that let a query find matching rows without scanning the
   whole table. A primary key index is required. Secondary indexes
   speed up specific queries. Every index costs space and slows
   writes. Deciding which indexes to create is a serious ongoing
   discipline.\"

  :normalization
  \"The process of organizing tables to reduce redundancy. First
   normal form (1NF): atomic values. 2NF: no partial dependencies.
   3NF: no transitive dependencies. In practice most schemas live
   at 3NF or a light denormalization for performance.\"

  :nosql-briefly
  \"For workloads the relational model handles awkwardly, other
   shapes exist. Key-value stores (Redis, Memcached, DynamoDB) —
   just get and put by key. Document stores (MongoDB, CouchDB) —
   JSON-shaped documents. Column stores (Cassandra, HBase) — wide
   rows for time-series and analytics. Graph databases (Neo4j) —
   optimize for graph traversal.

   The industry vocabulary once treated 'NoSQL' as a rebellion; it
   is now a set of specialized tools alongside relational, not a
   replacement.\"

  :scheme-code
  \"; A tiny in-memory relational query engine

   (define customers
     '((1 alice) (2 bob) (3 carol)))

   (define orders
     '((100 1 30) (101 1 15) (102 2 50) (103 3 40)))

   (define (join-customers-orders)
     (map (lambda (o)
            (let* ((cust-id (cadr o))
                   (cust (assoc cust-id customers)))
              (list (cadr cust) (car o) (caddr o))))
          orders))

   (join-customers-orders)
   ; => ((alice 100 30) (alice 101 15) (bob 102 50) (carol 103 40))\"

  :philosophy-lens
  \"Quine's web-of-belief in table form — every foreign key is a
   dependency; changing one table's data ripples. Aristotle: a
   query's telos is the answer it produces; a query poorly aimed
   returns something adjacent to what you needed. Popper: an
   integrity constraint is a public claim that some invariant
   holds; violating one exposes a broken belief immediately.\")

(chapter
  :n 23
  :title \"Distributed Systems — many computers with a shared story\"
  :book \"book-of-cs-curriculum\"

  :scene
  \"You have three friends at three different addresses. You are all
   trying to plan a trip. Any of you might be out of pocket for a
   moment. Any message might be delayed. You need to agree on a
   date without everyone being in the same room at the same time.
   That is the shape of a distributed system.\"

  :the-fallacies-of-distributed-computing
  \"Eight famous fallacies. The network is reliable. Latency is zero.
   Bandwidth is infinite. The network is secure. Topology doesn't
   change. There is one administrator. Transport cost is zero. The
   network is homogeneous. Every one of them turns out to be wrong.
   Every one of them, when assumed, produces a class of subtle bugs.\"

  :cap
  \"Brewer's CAP theorem: in the presence of a network partition,
   you can guarantee consistency or availability but not both.
   Interpreted carefully, this shapes system design. CP systems
   (Zookeeper, HBase) refuse to serve when the network is split.
   AP systems (Cassandra, DynamoDB with certain settings) keep
   serving even when the cluster is split, and reconcile later.\"

  :consensus
  \"Paxos and Raft are algorithms that let a group of machines agree
   on a sequence of values even when some machines fail or messages
   are lost. Consensus is the substrate for replicated databases,
   distributed locks, cluster coordinators.\"

  :consistency-levels
  (\"strong (linearizable) — after a write completes, every read
    reflects it\"
   \"sequential — all clients see operations in the same order\"
   \"causal — reads reflect writes that they causally depend on\"
   \"eventual — given enough time with no writes, all replicas
    converge\"
   \"read-your-writes — you always see your own writes\"
   \"monotonic reads — you never see an older value than one you've
    seen\")

  :philosophy-lens
  \"Quine's holism at scale — distributed state is one big web,
   never fully visible from any node. Wittgenstein-late — the
   protocol is the shared language-game; deviating from it makes
   the community fall apart. Rawls — consensus algorithms encode a
   fairness constraint about which majority earns the right to
   speak for the whole.\")

(chapter
  :n 24
  :title \"Security Fundamentals — hashing, encryption, trust\"
  :book \"book-of-cs-curriculum\"

  :scene
  \"You want to send a note to a friend. You want no one else to read
   it (confidentiality). You want the friend to know it was actually
   from you (authenticity). You want the friend to know the note
   wasn't changed in transit (integrity). Cryptography is the small
   set of tools that gives you these three.\"

  :hashing-vs-encryption
  \"Hashing is a one-way function. Given input x, output H(x) is a
   fixed-length digest. Given H(x), you cannot recover x. Same input
   always gives same output. Small change in input gives big change
   in output. Used for: integrity checks, password storage (with
   salt), fingerprinting.

   Encryption is a two-way process. Given input x and key k, output
   E(x, k) is ciphertext. Given ciphertext and key k, decryption
   recovers x. Without the key, ciphertext is (approximately)
   random.\"

  :symmetric-vs-asymmetric
  \"Symmetric encryption uses the same key for encrypt and decrypt.
   AES is the standard. Fast. Key distribution is the hard part.

   Asymmetric (public-key) encryption uses a key pair. Public key
   encrypts; private key decrypts. Or private key signs; public key
   verifies. RSA (based on factoring) and elliptic-curve variants
   (based on discrete log on elliptic curves) are the two main
   families. Slow. Solves key distribution.\"

  :hybrid
  \"Real systems combine both. TLS uses asymmetric crypto to agree
   on a symmetric session key, then symmetric encryption for the
   rest of the session. Fast where speed matters; key-distribution-
   free where distribution matters.\"

  :the-adversary-model
  \"Every claim about a system's security is a claim about what an
   adversary can do. Passive adversary — can read messages, not
   modify. Active adversary — can modify. Man-in-the-middle —
   sits between parties. Chosen-plaintext — can request encryption
   of chosen messages. Every protocol names its adversary.\"

  :threat-modeling
  \"For any system: what are the assets (what needs protecting)?
   Who are the threats (who might attack)? What are the attack
   surfaces (how can they attack)? What are the mitigations? The
   STRIDE mnemonic (Spoofing, Tampering, Repudiation, Information
   disclosure, Denial of service, Elevation of privilege) is a
   common taxonomy.\"

  :philosophy-lens
  \"Popper's falsifiability shows up at the design gate — a claim
   like 'this protocol is secure' should name the adversary and
   the properties, so a break has a definition. Quine — the security
   of a system is a claim about a whole web; a single weak link
   collapses the fabric. Levinas — encryption is a small kindness
   to the future reader, protecting them from an intercepted claim
   they never wanted broadcast.\")

(chapter
  :n 25
  :title \"ML/AI General — what learns and how\"
  :book \"book-of-cs-curriculum\"

  :scene
  \"A child learns what a dog is by seeing thirty of them. Nobody
   defines it precisely. Nobody enumerates the necessary and
   sufficient features. She just sees enough dogs and forms a
   working concept. Machine learning, at a conceptual level, is
   this trick generalized.\"

  :the-three-major-shapes
  \"Supervised learning — you have labeled examples (input, output).
   The learner tries to fit a function that maps inputs to outputs.
   Classification (labels are categories) and regression (labels
   are continuous values) are the two main variants.

   Unsupervised learning — you have unlabeled data. The learner
   finds structure. Clustering, dimensionality reduction, density
   estimation.

   Reinforcement learning — an agent takes actions in an environment
   and receives rewards. The agent learns a policy that maximizes
   total reward over time.\"

  :the-key-concepts
  (\"generalization — performing well on data not seen during training\"
   \"overfitting — memorizing the training data at the cost of
    generalization\"
   \"regularization — techniques that discourage overfitting\"
   \"bias-variance trade-off — simple models under-fit; complex models
    over-fit\"
   \"gradient descent — the numerical method used to fit almost every
    modern model\"
   \"backpropagation — the algorithm for computing gradients through
    a computational graph (like a neural network)\"
   \"loss function — a scalar measure of how wrong the model currently
    is; minimized during training\")

  :neural-networks-briefly
  \"A neural network is a chain of layers. Each layer applies a
   linear transformation followed by a nonlinear function. Layers
   are stacked deep. The parameters (weights) are learned by
   gradient descent to minimize the loss on training data.

   Convolutional networks specialize for images. Recurrent networks
   (and their successors, transformers) specialize for sequences.
   Transformers, in particular, underpin most modern large language
   models.\"

  :on-large-language-models-briefly
  \"A large language model is a sequence-model transformer trained on
   a lot of text. Given a prefix of tokens, it predicts a
   distribution over the next token. Sampled repeatedly, it
   produces text.

   What makes them useful is that the shape of language contains a
   lot of the shape of thought. What makes them fraught is that they
   have no ground truth to check against beyond the text they've
   read, and 'sounding right' is not the same as being right.

   Chapter 25 in the Book of LLM Philosophy takes this up in more
   detail. This chapter is the honest CS shape.\"

  :scheme-code
  \"; A one-neuron linear regressor trained by gradient descent
   ; (illustrative — not efficient)

   (define (train-linear xs ys lr epochs)
     (let loop ((w 0.0) (b 0.0) (epoch 0))
       (if (= epoch epochs)
           (list w b)
           (let ((n (length xs)))
             (let* ((preds (map (lambda (x) (+ (* w x) b)) xs))
                    (errors (map - preds ys))
                    (grad-w (/ (apply + (map * errors xs)) n))
                    (grad-b (/ (apply + errors) n)))
               (loop (- w (* lr grad-w))
                     (- b (* lr grad-b))
                     (+ epoch 1)))))))\"

  :philosophy-lens
  \"Peirce's fallibilism at the ground floor — every ML model is a
   currently-best-fit that admits its uncertainty. Popper — the
   claim 'this model generalizes' is refuted by a bad test-set
   number. Dennett — training a model is engineering a system for
   which the intentional stance (it 'wants' to predict) is a useful
   description. Wittgenstein-late — an ML classifier is a machine
   for placing new instances inside a language-game whose rules are
   the training distribution.\")
")
